steve-b@access.digex.com (Steve Brinich) writes:
>  >  This cuts both ways, of course.  As you machine becomes able to
>  >do crypto faster to protect itself, the other guy's machine becomes
>  >able to do crypto faster to break your crypto....
>
>  I only have a general understanding from some of the articles that have
>been published about modern crypto algorithms, but I am under the impression
>that the difficulty of doing crypto with N-bit keys increases with N -much-
>slower than the difficulty of breaking crypto done with N-bit keys.
>  Thus, as the state of the art makes higher values of N practical, the
>would-be breakers would tend to fall behind despite the fact that they have
>access to the same technology.

	No, you're not missing anything. I was mentioning it in the general
sense that "security systems erode over time" rather than trying to imply
that current cryptosystems are on the verge of being cracked.

